7:17 GMT"}],"update_date":"2013-09-20"}
{"id":"1301.1244","submitter":"Dmitri Sokolovski","authors":"Dmitri Sokolovski","title":"Path integral approach to space-time probabilities: a theory without\n  pitfalls but with strict rules","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevD.87.076001","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Following the renewed interest in the topic [1], we revisit the problem of\nassigning probabilities to classes of Feynman paths passing through specified\nspace-time regions. We show that by assigning of probabilities to interfering\nalternatives, one already makes an assumption that the interference has been\ndestroyed through interaction with an environment, or a meter. Including the\neffects of the meter allows to construct a consistent theory, free of logical\n'pitfalls' identified in Ref. [1]. Wherever a meter cannot be constructed, or\ncannot be set to perform the desired decoherence, formally constructed\nprobabilities have no clear physical meaning, and can violate the necessary sum\nrules. We illustrate the above approach by analysing the three examples\nconsidered in [1].\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 7 Jan 2013 16:08:44 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 18 Jan 2013 15:42:02 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-12"}
